\&\esubsecidx{ellap}\f(CW\*(C`(E,p,{\*(C'\fR\fIflag\fR\f(CW\*(C` = 0})\*(C'\fR: computes the \f(CW\*(C`a_p\*(C'\fR corresponding to the
elliptic curve \f(CW\*(C`E\*(C'\fR and the prime number \f(CW\*(C`p\*(C'\fR. These are defined by the
equation \f(CW\*(C`#E(\*(C'\fR\fBF\fR\f(CW\*(C`_p) = p+1 \- a_p\*(C'\fR, where \f(CW\*(C`#E(\*(C'\fR\fBF\fR\f(CW\*(C`_p)\*(C'\fR stands for the number
of points of the curve \f(CW\*(C`E\*(C'\fR over the finite field \fBF\fR\f(CW\*(C`_p\*(C'\fR. When \fIflag\fR is \f(CW0\fR,
this uses the baby-step giant-step method and a trick due to Mestre. This
runs in time \f(CWO(p^{1/4})\fR and requires \f(CWO(p^{1/4})\fR storage, hence becomes
unreasonable when \f(CW\*(C`p\*(C'\fR has about 30 digits.
.PP
If \fIflag\fR is \f(CW1\fR, computes the \f(CW\*(C`a_p\*(C'\fR as a sum of Legendre symbols. This is
slower than the previous method as soon as \f(CW\*(C`p\*(C'\fR is greater than 100, say.
.PP
